title: For Sale:  Engraved nickle plated 25 ACP, no FFL required (C&R)
postcontent:
I recently inherited this pistol from my grandmother, who kept it in her nightstand and occasionally carried it.  It is a Star model CO with nickle plate and engraving.  Magazine holds 7 rounds and it is safe to carry with one in the chamber giving it an 8 round capacity.  Pistol has been testfired and cleaned, functions perfectly.  These CO series pistols were hand fitted and comparable in quality to a Colt.  Pistol has an external hammer with a half-cock notch as well as an external safety which does not need to be utilized for pocket carry.  This type of pistol is typically carried hammer down, safety off.  Some time ago the original Pearlite grips cracked and were replaced with top quality reproductions from vintagegungrips.com for $50 (I know because I replaced them for her).  Original nickle finish is 90%.  Excellent overall condition, less than 50 rounds down the pipe (rounds included are from the original box purchased with the gun).  Steel frame and slide makes it durable enough to fire hot loads from Winchester and Cor-Bon.  This pistol was manufactured and imported in 1955 which means it is over 50 years old and exempt from the background check requirement and does not require transfer at an FFL, however I reserve the right not to sell this to anyone I do not like.

I am asking $350 cash for this pistol.  Comes with a full magazine and a padded carrying case.  Very compact, smaller than an LCP or a KelTec, carries well in a size 2 pocket holster.  I can meet anywhere in the greater Denver metro area, from Lakewood to Aurora, at a time and place of mutual convenience.  Prefer not to ship, but could do so if you are willing to pay via PayPal gift with an additional $30 to cover shipping from my FFL to yours.  Not interested in any trades, unless it's a J-frame (S&W, Charter Arms, Taurus).  Please reply with a phone number and general location.  Microtech in photo was recently sold and is no longer available.  Thanks.

postcontent: Butt and Forestock are checkered, this is the "Deluxe Border" model in .38/.357 Magnum and the 20" octagon barrel with adjustable front and rear sights and case hardening. Winchester’s1873 rifle was the “Rifle that Won the West.” It is chambered in the economical .38/.357 Magnum cartridge. A cowboy could have both a lever-action rifle and his six shooter, and needed only one cartridge belt for both. Most Texas Rangers and every old West cowboy worth his salt carried 1873 rifles. Chappo, the son of Apache war chief Geronimo, packed an 1873. And Buffalo Bill carried an 1873 lever-action rifle along with a pair of .44-40 Colts in 1876 when he worked as an Army scout. This piece of rifle history is available in a variety of distinctive models including this Special Cimarron branded Deluxe Short rifle. Don't let that fool you though, it has a 10+1 capacity and power to spare.

title: For Sale:  Very Unique Single Shot Hinged Block French Musket Converted to 12 Gauge via Snider System
location: Burlington - Skagit County, Mount Vernon, Washington
postcontent:
I have for sale a very interesting single shot hinged block shotgun.   It started out life as a  state of the art French Muzzle-loading musket in the 1850's, when France ruled more of the world than any other nation! It was converted to .577 breech loading rifle when the muzzle loading firearms became obsolete, probably in 1864.  Since .577 is very close to 12-gauge, the rifle were later converted again to 12-gauge by reaming out the rifling.  It shoots standard 2 3/4" 12-gauge shot shells.  I had a couple of gun smiths look it over, and they agreed it would be safe to shoot with light target loads.  I have fired it with such loads (7 1/2 Federals), and it works as it should.  It is actually fun to shoot!

The snider conversion was a unique system that employs a block that hinges over to allow access to the breech.  after firing, the block is hinged open, then pulled back to eject the spent cartridge.  The hammer, trigger and lock mechanism, butt plate and all the screws  appear to all be original 1853 French Musket.  

The stock is very beautiful, with excellent grain and contrast.   It's very elegantly shaped, with classic lines.  There are no cracks or damage that I can see.  The bluing on the iron parts is in quite good condition, and all work as they should.   It has obviously been used, but is in great condition considering it's over 160 years old!   The front sight is a brass bead.
The barrel is about 35" long.

I can e-mail more pictures; AL only lets me list one now for some reason.  It looks beautiful in person; the picture is grainy on AL.  I can send better, more clear pictures.

Since this was manufactured (and converted) before 1898, it can be sold without going through an FFL - so no transfer fee or tax.  I will need to see ID for my records, but no additional fees.  I may be interested in trades, but most likely only old firearms with wood furniture/ grips.

Thanks for looking, and have a great day!

location: Lutz/Land O' Lakes, Tampa/St. Pete, Florida
postcontent:
I have acquired this firearm from my grandfather who is very old and does not use it. I am not a trap shooter so I have very little use for it. It is a 12 gauge SKB 85TSS with a trap combo that includes two barrel kits (one 34" unsingle barrel with adjustable rib, and the other being a 32" over and under ventilated rib barrel ). In addition this combo brings a full set of factory SKB chokes and some aftermarket competition chokes totaling 11 chokes combined. The shotgun also features an adjustable cheek piece and an adjustable GraCoil recoil pad. It comes with accessories and tools (pictured) including a custom SKB hard case, a multi-choke wrench/tool, and a set of multiple HIVIZ sights in a neat holder. Needless to say this is a serious competition gun with everything you need to get started in the sport of trap, skeet, or bird hunting.

These open-tipped rounds until now have been available only to Special Operations Command troops.  SOCOM developed the new rounds for use with the Special Operations Force Combat Assault Rifle - Heavy, or SCAR-H, which needed a more accurate bullet because its short barrel, at 16 inches.  Using an open-tip match round design common with some sniper ammunition, SOST rounds are designed to be “barrier blind,” meaning they stay on target better than existing rounds after penetrating windshields, car doors and other objects.  This round's little brother, the MK318 mod 0 is slated to be the replacement to M855 and M855A1 rounds.

title: For Sale:  Finnish Tikka Mosin Nagant Model 1891 Bolt Action Rifle, B Barrel, 1942 C&R
postcontent:
Make:  Tikka Arsenal; Tikkakoski, Finland 

Model:  1891 (M91) 

Serial Number:  1098 

Year of Manufacture:  1942

Caliber:  7.62x54mm Rimmed (7.62x54R) 

Action Type:  Bolt Action with Fixed Magazine 

Markings:  The import mark on the barrel reads “M91 FINLAND 7.62R / C.A.I. ALB. ST. VT.” (See http://7.62x54r.net/MosinID/MosinM91F.htm to view information on the following markings.) The barrel shank is marked with the serial number “47950”, a Belgian barrel mark “B”, “1942” and with the Finnish ownership mark “SA” in a box. The bolt body and bottom of the magazine are marked with numbers "62458" that do not match the serial number "47950" that is marked in three different areas. The rear sight and base have a few small stampings on them. 

Barrel Length:  Approximately 31 ½” 

Sights / Optics:  The front sight is a dovetail set post. The rear sight is a “V” notched blade when in the down position. It is a “V” notched sliding elevator assembly when flipped up. The right side of the rear sight base is marked “2 3 4 5½ 7 8½” and the left side is marked "4 6 8 10 12". 

Stock Configuration & Condition:  The two piece hardwood stock has a straight grip, finger grooves, two barrel bands mounted through the sling eyelets, a through bolt, a cleaning rod and a metal buttplate. The refinished hardwood stock has various scrapes, scratches and compression marks. The gloss finish is pretty consistent. The LOP measures 13 5/8” from the front of the trigger to the back of the buttplate. The finish is original.

Overall Condition:  This rifle retains about 80% of its metal finish. The finish shows scrapes, light scratches, areas of frosting, thinning and pinprick surface erosion. There are areas of surface erosion on the bolt body, buttplate and sight ladder. The buttplate is scratched and pitted. The screw heads show light use. Overall, this rifle rates in Good to Very Good condition. 

Mechanics:  The action functions. We have not fired this rifle.
